<DocsLayout title="Tools & MCP" currentSlug="ai/mcp">
  <h1>Tools & MCP</h1>
  <p>
    A "tool" is just a function an agent's host can call on the model's
    behalf: read a file, run a command, query an API (see
    <a href="/docs/ai/hosts">LLMs vs. LLM hosts</a> for why it's the host
    doing the calling, not the model itself). The Model Context Protocol
    (MCP) is the standard for describing those tools so any compatible
    host can discover and call them the same way.
  </p>

  <h2>MCP is not a transport layer</h2>
  <p>
    The tempting analogy is "MCP is like HTTP/TCP but for LLMs" -- that's
    wrong. MCP is an <strong>application-layer protocol</strong> for
    connecting an agent to external capabilities: tools, resources
    (readable data), and prompts. It's JSON-RPC 2.0 on the wire, and the
    transport underneath is pluggable -- stdio for a local subprocess,
    or streamable HTTP for a remote server. MCP sits on top of a
    transport; it isn't one.
  </p>
  <p>
    The accurate one-liner: <strong>MCP is "LSP for AI agents."</strong>
    See <a href="/docs/ai/lsp">What is an LSP</a> for the full comparison
    -- same N&#215;M-to-N+M bet, same JSON-RPC foundation, deliberately
    modeled on LSP's approach.
  </p>

  <h2>The three primitives</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tools</strong> -- the model decides to call these (an <code>edit</code> or <code>grep</code> function, for example).</li>
    <li><strong>Resources</strong> -- readable data addressed by URI.</li>
    <li><strong>Prompts</strong> -- user-triggered templates, often surfaced as slash commands.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <code>cc-mcp</code>'s 89 stub tools (see <a href="/docs/mcp-server">
    MCP server</a>) are all the "Tools" primitive -- each has a name, a
    description, and a JSON Schema for its parameters, which is the
    contract a host validates calls against before ever invoking the
    (currently stubbed) handler.
  </p>

  <h2>The protocol is replaceable; adoption is what costs you</h2>
  <p>
    A tool's actual engine (the logic that does the work) and the
    protocol that exposes it to an agent are separate layers -- the
    engine doesn't know or care about MCP. You could invent your own
    protocol instead, and people did exactly that before MCP existed.
    The catch: no existing host knows how to speak your invented
    protocol, so you'd end up writing a shim that translates it into
    something hosts already understand -- which is the integration tax
    MCP exists to kill in the first place. MCP's value is the network
    effect, not the technical design.
  </p>

  <h2>stdio vs. HTTP</h2>
  <p>
    stdio transport (newline-delimited JSON, or Content-Length-framed
    JSON-RPC) suits a tool spawned as a local child process by the host.
    HTTP transport suits a long-running server other tools connect to
    over the network. <code>cc-mcp</code> supports both.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
